  "accepted_findings": [
    "AO-off is byte-identical to the alpha4 guide-seat reference and changes only an effectively negligible river-eye pixel fraction.",
    "Flat leaf normals change fewer than 0.03 percent of pixels in either corridor view, excluding sampled normals as the primary dark-crown cause.",
    "A bounded diagnostic emissive changes the crown response in both views and increases olive-green coverage, proving that project-owned source color reaches the material graph.",
    "LeafNormalStrength and LeafDiagnosticEmissive remain exposed at neutral defaults of 1 and 0 for repeatable diagnostics only."
  ],
  "rejection_reasons": [
    "AO-off and flat-normal modes retain the same nearly black, visually saturated crown masses as the V16 alpha4 reference.",
    "The emissive mode is deliberately non-physical and cannot substitute for plausible direct, ambient, or two-sided transmission lighting.",
    "Four-times alpha still destroys useful leaf-edge discrimination and remains visually close to constant opacity.",
    "None of the V17 modes produces a lifelike mixed-species Patagonian rainforest corridor."
  ],
  "next_iteration_requirements": [
    "Hold geometry, masks, placement, alpha4, leaf-shadow disable, exposure, and neutral material controls fixed while adding transient front and back fill lights matching the accepted isolated review rig.",
    "Capture a separate transient skylight-intensity and recapture treatment so direct-fill response can be distinguished from ambient-light response.",
    "If either treatment restores leaf color, implement a physically plausible corridor lighting or transmission correction without emissive fill and then reduce opacity scale below saturation.",
    "Repeat guide-seat and river-eye captures before adding the second ecology-reviewed canopy stratum or promoting any corridor substitution."
  ]
}
